cxt.interpretation: This layer appears to be late Roman fill of a cut in the bedrock that extends under wall 264, into room 31.
cxt.dating elements: Late Roman fragment of ceramic lamp
cxt.observations: This is definitely a separate layer but its separation from 781 is less clear. It appears that these are similar if not the same, just squeezed into a small space in the bedrock. Coin 3506 is a very clear issue of Diocletian of 284-85, struck at Rome, antoninian denomination -- but it has been confused between 780 and 781 (not mapped; register says 780, bag says 781).
cxt.description: This layer fills cut 729  in the S corner of the room, at the cut's S end.  It measures 70cm in length (of the greater cut that is 119cm) and it, at its widest point, 49cm wide, and at its narrowest, 36cm. It is teardrop-shaped as a result of the cut into the bedrock, and later wall built atop of it. The soil is medium brown and rather compact, including a fair amount of debris.
cxt.definition: Fill of semicircular cut in bedrock in S corner of room 38

cxt.observations: Compared to previous layers there were [far] fewer ceramics and bone. Proportionately there was more plaster. Nail found in very bottom of context. Very little tile at all. Uncertain whether 0782 was over 0845? No, it is under 0845. Ceramics suggest that 845 is earlier than 782; they also suggest that some part of 782 was contaminated by Middle Byzantine activity, since 772 seems Early Byz but is above 782 - intrusion with construction of well?
cxt.description: A soft brown loam with very few orange clay inclusions. Consistency was full of chunks of bedrock and other small stones. The dimensions of this context are 1.7 M (NE-SW) X 60 cm (N-W-SE) and approximately 5-7 cm in depth. This context covered small bits of what was left of context 0788, but it also seemed to cover areas of bedrock where 0788 was absent (0782 had similar characteristics in Area 2).
cxt.definition: Soft brown loam in NW courtyard
